or whatever.

113
00:04:05,824 --> 00:04:07,558
Question one:

114
00:04:07,559 --> 00:04:10,694
"What were your last words
with the deceased?"

115
00:04:10,695 --> 00:04:11,695
Lame.

116
00:04:11,696 --> 00:04:13,631
Question two:

117
00:04:13,632 --> 00:04:15,566
Wait...

118
00:04:15,567 --> 00:04:17,768
My last words with
Marvin were lovely.

119
00:04:17,769 --> 00:04:20,170
I've been thinking
about them a lot.

120
00:04:20,171 --> 00:04:21,138
Me, too.

121
00:04:21,139 --> 00:04:23,374
We went for a hike
in the snow

122
00:04:23,375 --> 00:04:24,508
and had this amazing talk.

123
00:04:24,509 --> 00:04:25,809
My last day with Pop,

124
00:04:25,810 --> 00:04:28,345
he taught my son
how to skate.

125
00:04:31,349 --> 00:04:33,450
Well, this is
clearly yielding nothing.

126
00:04:33,451 --> 00:04:34,518
Thanks, Dad.

127
00:04:34,519 --> 00:04:36,386
Guess I'll have
to fill the time

128
00:04:36,387 --> 00:04:38,855
with some jokes... again.
(scoffs)

129
00:04:39,491 --> 00:04:42,826
"Last words" seems
like a good theme.

130
00:04:42,827 --> 00:04:44,728
Marshall, do you
remember the last thing

131
00:04:44,729 --> 00:04:46,463
your father said to you?

132
00:04:47,449 --> 00:04:50,534
Bye, sweetie.
Bye, Mom.

133
00:04:50,535 --> 00:04:52,169
Son,

134
00:04:52,170 --> 00:04:55,839
there's something I want to say
before I leave.

135
00:04:55,840 --> 00:04:59,076
Yeah, Dad?

136
00:05:00,245 --> 00:05:03,747
Could I snag that extra
pork chop for the flight?

137
00:05:04,516 --> 00:05:06,417
I was gonna make
a sandwich with that, Dad.

138
00:05:06,418 --> 00:05:07,518
Ah...
Dad, don't they have

139
00:05:07,519 --> 00:05:08,519
food on the plane?

140
00:05:08,520 --> 00:05:11,989
Yeah, but plane food is ass.

141
00:05:13,158 --> 00:05:15,859
"Plane food is ass."

142
00:05:16,227 --> 00:05:17,728
Those are the last words

143
00:05:17,729 --> 00:05:20,064
my father will ever say to me.

144
00:05:20,065 --> 00:05:22,616
Right after I denied the man
a pork chop.

145
00:05:22,617 --> 00:05:24,234
Oh, God.

146
00:05:28,873 --> 00:05:29,907
Wait!

147
00:05:29,908 --> 00:05:30,941
I'm wrong!

148
00:05:30,942 --> 00:05:32,876
I'm wrong! That wasn't it!

149
00:05:32,877 --> 00:05:34,611
They couldn't find a cab...

150
00:05:34,612 --> 00:05:35,946
Hey, Marshall!

151
00:05:35,947 --> 00:05:38,581
<i>so my dad called up from
the street. Marshall!</i>

152
00:05:39,551 --> 00:05:40,951
Looks like rain out here!

153
00:05:40,952 --> 00:05:45,723
I couldn't find an umbrella in
your closet!

154
00:05:45,724 --> 00:05:47,491
You know who probably has
an umbrella?

155
00:05:47,492 --> 00:05:48,859
<i>And then, well, see,</i>

156
00:05:48,860 --> 00:05:51,762
<i>my dad grew up in a small town,
in another generation,</i>

157
00:05:51,763 --> 00:05:54,431
<i>so sometimes--
totally well-meaningly--</i>

158
00:05:54,432 --> 00:05:57,234
<i>he'd say stuff like...</i>

159
00:05:57,235 --> 00:06:00,037
The Koreans across the hall!

160
00:06:00,038 --> 00:06:03,407
Hey, the Koreans are a
trustworthy and generous people!

161
00:06:03,408 --> 00:06:04,708
Dad...

162
00:06:04,709 --> 00:06:07,444
I betcha one of the Koreans has
an umbrella!

163
00:06:07,445 --> 00:06:09,880
Heck, they're Koreans!

164
00:06:11,116 --> 00:06:14,651
My dad's last words to me
were a string

165
00:06:14,652 --> 00:06:17,421
of odd racial stereotypes.

166
00:06:17,422 --> 00:06:19,423
All that stuff
was really nice!

167
00:06:19,424 --> 00:06:21,592
Yeah!
It's positive racism!

168
00:06:21,593 --> 00:06:25,062
This is worse
than the pork chop.

169
00:06:26,097 --> 00:06:28,799
This next clip is entitled,
"Guy Playing Bagpipes

170
00:06:28,800 --> 00:06:32,136
Gets Hit in the Nuts
by Low-Flying Seagull""

171
00:06:32,137 --> 00:06:33,237
Let's see what happens.

172
00:06:33,238 --> 00:06:34,571
(bagpipes play
"Amazing Grace" on video)

173
00:06:34,572 --> 00:06:37,241
(seagulls squawking on video)
BOTH: Here he comes...

174
00:06:37,242 --> 00:06:40,144
(thud on video) Oh! Oh!

175
00:06:40,145 --> 00:06:42,279
(snickering)

176
00:06:42,280 --> 00:06:44,281
'Cause he gets hit
right in the nuts.

177
00:06:44,282 --> 00:06:48,552
BOTH: And then the fat kid
loses his swim trunks.

178
00:06:48,553 --> 00:06:50,204
Fall off. Shorts
just fall right off.

179
00:06:50,205 --> 00:06:51,238
No, wait-- I'm wrong.

180
00:06:51,239 --> 00:06:52,522
That wasn't it.

181
00:06:52,523 --> 00:06:54,491
They couldn't find a cab,
so I went down there.

182
00:06:54,492 --> 00:06:57,711
Hey, you were right.

183
00:06:57,712 --> 00:06:59,696
The Kangs did, in fact,
have an umbrella.

184
00:06:59,697 --> 00:07:01,582
Of course they did.

185
00:07:01,583 --> 00:07:02,499
Bye, sweetie.

186
00:07:02,500 --> 00:07:04,251
Bye, Mom.

187
